PromeTorch License
==================

Copyright (c) 2026 PromeTorch Contributors
Based on the BSD 3-Clause "New" or "Revised" License (the base license of
PyTorch, upon which PromeTorch is API-compatible).

This license is intentionally permissive. It is designed to let people
build, ship, sell, fork, and remix anything they want using PromeTorch.
The only restriction is that you cannot take PromeTorch itself, repackage
it as a product, and sell it.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or without
modification, are permitted provided that the following conditions are met:

1. Redistributions of source code must retain the above copyright notice,
   this list of conditions and the following disclaimer.

2. Redistributions in binary form must reproduce the above copyright notice,
   this list of conditions and the following disclaimer in the documentation
   and/or other materials provided with the distribution.

3. Neither the name "PromeTorch" nor the names of its contributors may be
   used to endorse or promote products derived from this software without
   specific prior written permission. (This does not restrict the
   attribution required by Section 4 — that is encouraged.)

4. ATTRIBUTION REQUIREMENT (commercial products and services).
   If you ship, sell, or operate a commercial product, application, or
   service that includes PromeTorch as a runtime, library, or component
   (this includes SaaS / hosted APIs, on-prem software, mobile apps,
   desktop software, hardware products with embedded inference, paid
   developer tools, and similar), you must include a visible attribution
   in at least ONE of the following places:

       (a) The product's About / Credits / Acknowledgements screen;
       (b) The product's documentation, README, or website;
       (c) The product's UI footer or splash screen;
       (d) The "open source notices" section of a mobile / desktop app.

   The attribution must read substantially:

       "Powered by PromeTorch — https://github.com/barometech/PromeTorch"

   You do NOT need to add attribution if PromeTorch is used purely
   internally (e.g. internal training pipelines, R&D, scripts that don't
   ship to end users), or for personal / educational / non-commercial
   use, or in research papers (citation is encouraged but not required).

5. NO RESALE OF THE FRAMEWORK ITSELF.
   You may NOT sell, license, sublicense, rent, lease, or otherwise
   monetarily distribute PromeTorch — in whole, in substantial part, or
   as a thin re-skin / wrapper — as a standalone product, library, SDK,
   framework, or toolkit. This includes:

       (a) Rebranding PromeTorch and selling it as a different-named
           framework or library;
       (b) Selling a "commercial edition" / "enterprise version" /
           "pro tier" of PromeTorch with paywalled core functionality;
       (c) Charging license fees, subscription fees, per-seat fees, or
           cloud-runtime fees for access to the framework itself
           (as opposed to fees for YOUR product that happens to use it);
       (d) Selling access to the source code of PromeTorch;
       (e) Bundling PromeTorch with a trivial wrapper / GUI / CLI shim
           and selling THAT as a "framework" product.

   The PromeTorch source code itself must remain freely and openly
   available to everyone.

6. PERMITTED USES (explicitly allowed, including at scale and for profit,
   with no further fees, no royalties, and no notification required —
   only the attribution in Section 4):

       (a) Training neural networks and machine-learning models with
           PromeTorch, for any purpose: research, internal business,
           client work, commercial products, paid services;
       (b) Running inference with models trained or built with
           PromeTorch — including as paid SaaS, paid APIs, paid
           on-prem deployments, shipped commercial software, embedded
           inference in hardware, paid mobile / desktop apps;
       (c) Selling, licensing, or monetizing the neural-network models,
           weights, training pipelines, application code, or services
           that USE PromeTorch as a runtime dependency. The models you
           train ARE YOURS. The pipelines you build ARE YOURS. The
           services you operate ARE YOURS;
       (d) Building and selling AI-powered applications, websites, SDKs,
           mobile apps, hardware products, agents, robotics systems,
           or anything else that embeds PromeTorch as a library;
       (e) Consulting, integration, custom training, fine-tuning, or
           deployment services delivered using PromeTorch;
       (f) Forking PromeTorch, modifying it, and using your fork
           internally or in your own products. If you redistribute a
           public fork (open source), it must remain under this license
           (or a strictly more permissive open license) and the resale
           restriction in Section 5 still applies — i.e. you can fork,
           but you cannot fork-and-sell-as-a-product;
       (g) Publishing derivative models, applications, papers, or
           research results trained on PromeTorch, commercial or
           non-commercial.

   In plain terms:
       - The framework is free, open, and yours to use.
       - Build whatever you want with it. Charge whatever you want for
         what YOU built.
       - Just attribute, and don't repackage and sell the framework
         itself as your own product.

